node.text:
I sent my dad in Chicago a box of workout equipment from the @silversneakers website store. I sent him 3-lb dumbells, a green (medium) resistance band with handles, three soft balls and a pump. The extra balls are for my mom and sister.

My dad has been taking my senior fitness zoom classes every week. My sister has been coming too! Lately, my dad had been using any vegetable or fruit he had laying around (like a cantaloupe or papaya) for the ball work portion. So, I decided to get him some official stuff!

Swipe to see his text to me. He was so excited! I’m happy the shipping took about two days!!!! 

Funny how the pandemic has me teaching my friends and family on zoom now!

Superinfections and coinfections can augment pathogenesis, increasing the morbidity and mortality of viral infections.”1
As of May 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic has spread across the globe, infecting over 3 million people, and causing over 200,000 deaths. In the past, some epidemics and pandemics have been found to be associated with varying levels of bacterial/fungal co-infections, which are a major cause of mortality. For example, data suggests that co-infection is associated with more severe outcomes in seasonal and pandemic influenza and may account for up to 30% of cases of Community Acquired Pneumonia. 
Studies have shown that antibiotics are being administered to a majority of hospitalized COVID-19 patients. While this protocol may be justified in light of the history of pandemic co-infections, there are also increasing concerns about the growing incidence of antibiotic resistance.  Therefore, researchers identified “a clinical need for robust investigation into co-infection in patients with COVID-19.2
In a systematic review and meta-analysis researchers evaluated thirty studies encompassing 3,834 patients hospitalized for COVID-19.  Results showed that patients in ICU wards had a higher proportion of bacterial co-infection than patients in ICU/mixed ward settings. The overall incidence of bacterial co-infection in hospitalized COVID-19 patients was 7%, while in studies that included only ICU patients the incidence was 14%. Other authors have estimated the overall incidence of secondary infection in COVID-19 patients to be between 10-30% of cases.2 The most common bacterial pathogens identified by this review are Mycoplasma pneumonia followed by Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Haemophilus influenzae, and Klebsiella pneumoniae. 
The prevalence of viral co-infections was 3%, with influenza A and Respiratory Syncytial Virus occurring most frequently. Co-infection with fungal pathogens was reported in only three of the studies included in this review. However, an increasing number of reports from Europe of COVID-19 patients with possible or probable pulmonary aspergillosis, suggests that further investigation into co-infection with fungal pathogens is warranted.

As a Work and Business Psychologist, I have received several emails and read articles that predict a higher risk of burnout. There are two reasons for this: the ongoing impact of the pandemic and the fallout associated with systemic discrimination in the workplace.

Burnout has been a major problem in the modern workplace, but it doesn't get as much attention as it should since it's rarely discussed openly.

When chronic stress causes you to dread your job and hate going to work – or if the stress becomes all-consuming, leading to mental and physical exhaustion -- you’re probably suffering from burnout.

In some cases, people are in a position or on a career path that is unsuitable for them. Sometimes there’s a poor match between the person and the management style or organizational culture. In other cases, there can be serious bullying or harassment.

So, what’s the solution?

In this August 19th group coaching and training session, we’ll discuss:

• What is burnout?
• What are the signs of burnout?
• What are the consequences?
• Prevention and survival techniques

Registration is on Eventbrite (or send a DM for a clickable link)

This year has been extremely difficult for me and many of you as well. It is very easy to get stuck in a never ending place of sadness and anxiety... so on Wednesday I decided to do a self care project and photograph myself. I ended up with images that were anywhere from sad, confused, mad, sassy, goofy, happy, to just blurry ??‍???. Which I guess explains this year. 
.
.
I have heard from many of you and I want to thank you for the kind words. I wasn’t doing it for compliments - I simply wanted to show the person, the “ME” I miss. My self care has been put at the bottom of the list by me, myself and I... and that is not okay. 
.
.
I wasn’t sure if I was going to post any of these photos. Women especially are judged on their appearance — Breaking News! — and how they present themselves no matter what they intend. Women are labeled angry, too sexy, ditzy, crazy, bossy, nasty, mad and the list goes on. Women are judged. Period. Even though I felt very vulnerable, I also felt empowered. ?? I’m hearing that some are sexy and I’m going to own that! ?? ?
.
.
I decided to push through feelings of anxiety that have increased during this pandemic - MANY of you know how this feels - and I decided to 1.)Shower 2.)Do my hair 3.)Put on makeup 4.)Have fun AND 5.)Not fix the photos with filters or other editing - with the exception being a black & white filter from Instagram. ?
.
#BeKind to yourself today. ?
.
.
NOTE: I placed a fan behind the camera because I was extremely warm and a lot of the shine aka glow on my face is just good ole sweat. ??
.
.
.

node.text:
Who knew 2020 was gonna be such a difficult year. A pandemic and the world shuts down. Children are homeschooled and lose their social connections, people.start working from home others are furloughed, jobs are lost. Some relish the time they get to spend with their families while others struggle with their new normal. 

We realise our life as we knew it may not return and if it does it won't be anytime soon. Travel while at the start of the year is a fun adventure is now a dangerous thought. Quarantines are imposed, borders shut and 2020 becomes the year of the staycation.

Who would have thought that we would be wearing masks to do the grocery shop and washing/sanitising our hands a million times daily. 

What has 2020 become?

I for one look forward to 2021 and the hope of travelling like we did a few months ago returning. Maybe we will forevermore be cautious, maybe hand sanitising and masks will always be at the ready but i hope that soon i will be living this picture and off pn a new adventure and safety and calmness of mind will return.

#travelagentlife #lovetotravel #mumlife

Billy & Jason
New York City
•
Pride Reclaimed
“The Queer Liberation March for BLM was incredible. Energetic, aggressive, peaceful. 
•
“Navigating a pandemic, we’d been in quarantine since early March and we had struggled with the urgency to participate in the BLM protests. Soon, the data confirmed that the protests didn’t contribute to spikes in the virus. When the march was reorganized as a protest, we decided it was time to join our voices to the movement. 
•
“We’ve been to many parades, but that Sunday felt like Pride. No cops. No corporations. Black Lives Matter. Black Trans Lives Matter. Stonewall was a riot. Pride is a protest.”
•
“Pride was not cancelled; it was reclaimed.”
@puppyfootlife

node.text:
@4oakcliff Wanna help? We STILL need volunteers at EACH location!
———
Set-Up/Unloading
Traffic Direction
Backpack Distro
Replenishment
Greeters

HERE’S HOW TO VOLUNTEER:
———
1. SHOW UP at one of the 4 locations listed on the #swipe. MASK required. Arrive at 6:30am

2. Park in designated Volunteer Parking ONLY.

3. Check-in at the Volunteer tent on your site. Arrive 15 minutes early.

4. Partner with your site manager to offer hands-on assistance!

5. If you’ve experienced any Covid symptoms or been exposed to Covid in the last 3 days, please stay home.

The festival will start at 9am til noon at each location. Come ready to WORK work!

Email Sydney.chandler@foroakcliff.org with questions or DM @stefonique.
——
FAQs:

Can kids volunteer?
Yes.

Can groups volunteer?
Yes.

What to wear?
Activewear. Tennis shoes.

Can I show up after 6:30am?
Yes. As long as it’s before 10am WE NEED YOU!

Can I pass out info at the festival?
No.

Can I work at more than one site?
No. Bloom where you’re planted!

Can I get a shirt?
Shirts are first come, first serve.

Will For Oak Cliff be checking temperatures and providing PPE?
For volunteers, yes. -

node.text: Great for the environment AND you.

#riding my #bike has been one of my favorite #ACTIVities during the #pandemic. Upstate NY took a hit, and one of my favorite places on earth, @bertsbox, can’t physically open back up just yet. #nyregulationsruineverything So, I take advantage of a beautiful #summer and take some #preworkout and then pedal for as long or far as I want. Not racing right now, just riding. Working on keeping in decent #shape for the @transplantgamesofamerica in July 2021! Thank you @fnx_fit for fueling my workouts! I love a Vanilla Milkshake protein shake when I’m done! node.text:
Managing COVID-19 at Home

Treatments for COVID-19 – remdesivir and dexamethasone – are proven effective for hospitalized patients. Most infected patients will have less severe symptoms and will be advised to stay at home if they are breathing adequately. Treatment at home is supportive. That means rest, drinking plenty of fluids, acetaminophen (Tylenol or paracetamol) for fevers and aches, and monitoring symptoms. There is no evidence that prescription medication (eg hydroxychloroquine) helps treat infection or prevents it from progressing to more severe illness. Click our bio link for complete patient information.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'MULTI TASKING.... The new generation moms.... Always do something more.... Take care of the house, children, cooking, working from home.... Just want to be independent.... So you have to work smart.... RIGHT...?'.
Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: 2 people.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'Memasak terkadang membutuhkan wak?u yang lama. Apalagi proses persiapan bahan hingga pengolahan bisa membuang banyak terutama bagi Anda yang sibuk. Rangkaian memasak bukan hanya sekedar mencampurkan bahan makanan. Akan tetapi Anda harus mencuci sayuran, mengupas bumbu, menghaluskan bumbu sampai mendidihkan air. Agar semua pekerjaan bisa diselesaikan dengan baik, RealSimple punya beberapa tips untuk Anda agar tak berlama-lama di dapur.'.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says '12 11 KITCH HEN RULES SAYCR LBOWSO Untiyou're nkYou ate!HELP CLEAN Napkin Lap SPEAK 1. TENTUKAN WAKTU ANDA Sebelum memasak, pastikan Anda sudah membaca resep dengan baiksecara keseluruhan. Kemudian siapkan bahan hingga alat serta tentukan menu makanan apa yang ingin Andaa sajikan. Hindari memasak makanan yang membutuhkan perhatian konstan ayam panggang. Jika Anda hendak membuat sarapan, sebaiknya rencanakan dan siapkan bahannya pada malam hari, agar keesokan harinya Anda tidak kerepotan untuk menyiapkan bahan makanan.'.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: one or more people, text that says '2. GUNAKAN JASA DELIVERY 228311000 Belanja memang bisa menghabiskan banyak waktu dan tenaga. Pesan beberapa kebutuhan dapur seperti beras, kacang kaleng, sayuran beku, pasta, tomat, dan lain sebagainya ggunakanj jasa pengiriman atau memesan belanjaan via online. Dengan demikian, waktu Anda untuk berbelanja di supermarket ataupun pasa akan lebih cepat dan tidak lagi membutuhkan daftar list yang panjang'.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says '3. LENGKAPI DAPUR ANDA Dapur yang lengkap dengan bahan makanan tentu akan menghemat waktu memasak. Kulkas Anda harus diisi dengan makanan yang Anda sukai dan paling sering dimasak, sehingga saat ingin memasak Anda tidak perlu berpikir panjang masakan apa yang akan Anda santap. Anda bisa saja melengkapi kulkas Anda dengan sosis beku, kacang polong, keju, atau sayuran brokoli dan perseteli. Agar lebih memudahkannya lagi, bisa juga menyimpan pasta, biji-bijian dan makanan kaleng di kulkas Anda.'.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says '4. ALAT BANTU MEMASAK MEMOTONG BAHAN MAKANAN MEMANG MEMERLUKAN KETERAMPILAN YANG TINGGI AGAR CEPAT DALAM MEMOTONG MENGGUNAKAN PISAU. NAMUN, BAGAIMANA JIKA ANDA MEMBUTUHKAN WAKTU BANYAK HANYA UNTUK MEMOTONG DAN MENYIAPKAN BAHAN MAKANANNYA SAJA? UNTUK MEMBANTU MASAKAN CEPAT MATANG, GUNAKAN FOOD PROCESSOR UNTUK MENCINCANG DAN MENGIRIS SAYURAN, RICE COOKER UNTUK MEMASAK DAGING, OVEN, DAN BLENDER UNTUK MEMBANTU ANDA DALAM TAHAP PENYIAPAN BAHAN MAKANAN NAN'.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says '5. MEMASAK DALAM JUMLAH BESAR SAAT INGIN MEMASAK, PIKIRKAN UNTUK BERAPA ORANG MAKANAN TERSEBUT AKAN DI SANTAP. JIKA HANYA UNTUK SEORANG DIRI, SEBAIKNYA ANDA MENYAJIKAN MAKANAN UNTUK DUA ORANG, JIKA UNTUK DUA ORANG MAKA ANDA MENY AJIKANNYA UNTUK EMPAT SETERUSNY A. MAKANAN SISA DAPAT ANDA SIMPAN DENGAN BAIK DALAM WADAH DI DALAM FREEZER. KETIKA AKAN MEMAKANNYA CUKUP DIHANGATKAN KEMBALII SEHINGGA LEBIH MENGHEMAT WAKTU. Aa'.

Photo by RESTO 52 on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: text that says '6. MENYIMPAN DI KULKAS Menyimpan makanan tidak hanya praktis, juga hemat. Tidak hanya terbatas pada makanan yang sudah bumbu bisa disimpan. Selama saya terbiasa menyimpan hasil gilingan bawang merah dan putih yang sudah ditumis dalam toples kecil di kulkas. Bagaimana jika kita ingin menyimpan makanan yang sudah adi i'atau setengah di freezer? Oow, pasti bisa, dong. Banyak sekali makanan yang bisa kita simpan freezer. tulisan yang pernah saya baca menyebutkan bahwa prinsipnya semua makanan jadi kita simpan, termasuk kue. Untuk menyimpan makanan di freezer, bisa digunakan plastik untuk pendingin, plastik untuk alat dan wadah kedap udara.'.

node.text: DROP IT OFF AT THE DOE!!!!
DROP IT OFF AT THE DOE!!!!

The #USPostalService (#USPS) removed #mailboxes in parts of #Oregon as city officialssay they've seen a significant decline in mail volume.

"First-class mail volume has declined significantly in the #US, especially since the #pandemic," #ErnieSwanson, a spokesman for the USPS,told #TheOregonian."That translates to less mail in collection boxes."
Swanson said that the change shouldn't affect service, such as pickup times and processing of mail. Another USPS source told the outlet that boxes were being replaced with higher-security ones.

The USPS has seen a significantly decline in revenue, and onThursday President#Trump suggestedthat he was unwilling to make a deal with #Democrats that included providing funding for the #PostalService.

Trump has repeatedly argued that increased mail-in voting could lead to more voter fraud, though there is no evidence to suggest that's the case. He said Thursday he wasn't keen on providing the Postal Service with more money because it could ease mail-in voting.

"They want $25 billion forthepost office.Now,they need that money in order to have the post office work so it can take all ofthese millions and millions of ballots," Trump said. "Now in the meantime, they aren't getting there. By the way, those are just two items. But if they don't get those two items that means youcan't have universal mail-in voting,becausethey're not equipped to have it." #TheSavageRoom #Savage

node.text:
“We were able to visit her every day and that was so important to us.”

Christian shares his story about his mother, Helen, her time here at St Luke’s, and the wonderful experience they had as a family despite the restrictions of the pandemic.

The coronavirus pandemic is having a devastating effect on St Luke’s financially, and we know its impact won’t go away quickly. It is a long term threat.

A regular monthly donation set up today offers sustainability to ensure St Luke’s is still here, in Sheffield, now and for many generations to come.

Will you give what you can?

Please visit www.stlukeshospice.org.uk/monthly-donation. Link in bio.

node.text:
Sara El Beshbichi
Milan, Italy 
•
“I'm a fashion photographer and I'm used to beauty. But I've never been self confident. During the lockdown my possibility to shot with models reduced, so I decided to try something on myself.
•
“People can say that you're beautiful, but it will never be real until you'll belive it.
•
“Also, I've always enjoyed makeup. It's another way to paint! And that's the result. Maybe it's not my best shots, but it's surely one of the most difficult for me.”
@saraelbesh

node.text: Hoppy Friday! It has been quite a year so far, huh? Things may seem like they are getting better here in NYC, but we can't relax just yet and risk a proper second wave. @kegandlanternredhook is here to remind you to stay vigilant with their 6 Feet Apart IPA, hopped with Simcoe, Hallertau Blanc, and Amarillo. This beer has a nice soft and juicy citrus flavor, but also a grassy green tea note to it. Honey biscuit malt flavors tie the whole thing together. I couldn't place the glass and can 6 feet apart for the photo, but that's ok because I couldn't stay far from the beer for long anyway! Stay safe out there folks!

shortcode_media.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bj Pugh-Jupiter on August 14, 2020. Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'Dolly Parton Supports Black Lives Matter: 'Our Little White Asses' Aren't All That Matters The country music legend says she's in favor of the push push for racial justice and understands the importance of being "felt and seen." By Jeremy Blum 08/13/2020 08:36 PMET IG:Locdsp1r1t 9u5 PHOTOG 01:22'.

node.text:
#DollyParton has voiced her indisputable support for #BlackLivesMatter as well as the importance of changing with the times.

“I understand people having to make themselves known and felt and seen,” the 74-year-old Parton said, referring to the latest wave of racial justice #protests sweeping the United States. “And of course Black lives matter. Do we think our little white asses are the only ones that matter? No!” 

The Queen of Country also explained her 2018 decision to rename the Dixie Stampede dinner attraction, a Southern-themed horse-riding and pyrotechnics show in Missouri and Tennessee, after it was called a “lily-white kitsch extravaganza that play-acts the Civil War but never once mentions slavery” in a 2017 Slate article.

“There’s such a thing as innocent ignorance, and so many of us are guilty of that,” Parton said. “When they said ‘Dixie’ was an offensive word, I thought, ‘Well, I don’t want to offend anybody. This is a business. We’ll just call it The Stampede.’ As soon as you realize that [something] is a problem, you should fix it. Don’t be a dumbass. That’s where my heart is. I would never dream of hurting anybody on purpose.” 

Parton dropped the word “Dixie,” often used to describe the American South during the time of slavery, about 2 years before The Dixie Chicks followed suit in June, renaming themselves The Chicks. 

Other segments of the interview detail Parton’s role during the #COVID_19 #pandemic, including the singer’s donation of $1 million toward #coronavirus research.

“As the Scripture says, ‘To whom much is given, much is required.’” Parton said. “So I look at my life with that every day and think that God expects it of me. ... If I can be an inspiration, then I want to be that. That makes me feel good.”

node.text:
Great beach day reading!

From Mike Lauterborn, the author of the adventurous 66-day road trip around America travelogue "Chasing Charley", comes a new book titled "Pandemonium", a detailed account of the Covid-19 pandemic from Dec. 31, 2019, when Wuhan, China announced its first cases, through America's Reopening in early June 2020, and everything in between. The shutdowns, the economic impacts, the safety measures instituted, the lifestyle changes, wacky weather, social disturbances and more, all from Mike's perspective on the southwestern CT shore just 40 miles from NYC, the epicenter of the outbreak. You'll be riveted as the crisis unfolds and we achieve a "new normal", identifying with many of the life alterations that have transpired.

Be among the first to order a copy, the premier book to emerge from this pandemic that presents both a newsy and intimate perspective on our public health crisis. 

Order here: https://www.authorhouse.com/en/bookstore/bookdetails/814505-pandemonium

node.text:
Sri is one of our epidemiologists whose pre-COVID work involved working with our aging populations. During the pandemic, she’s a perfect fit serving as our aging and long term care sector liaison. Building on her strengths, and a soft spot for working with older generations, she works closely with state and county partners to keep our older generations safe and healthy. It’s not an easy job, as our aging populations are at higher risk for severe COVID complications, and—like many of us—also want to maintain connections with loved ones. Luckily for Dane County, Sri has the expertise, experience, and empathy to inform practices that decrease risk while still addressing other critical health and human needs.
 
Recently, the Greater WI Agency on Aging Resources and the WI Aging Advocacy Network nominated Sri to be the aging representative on the State Disaster Medical Advisory Committee (SDMAC). We congratulate Sri and thank her for her ongoing commitment to support Dane County’s wise and wonderful elders!
.
.

@beltslee I’m going to be out in the garden a lot!
?? Yard work keeps me semi sane. Totally over all of it (as I wash my mask for today)

?. ??. ????. ??. ??? ???? ????? ???? ??? ? ????!⁣
⁣
I think being in healthcare and being a small business owner is its own special kind of hell during this pandemic. It’s a LOT to balance. Most of the time, I feel capable of handling the challenges with grace.⁣
⁣
But this week was hard, folx! Every day felt like⁣
a typical Monday.⁣
⁣
The good news is that the business side is stable. I mean, my practice isn’t as busy as it was pre-pandemic but my days are full of patients. My favorite part of my job is connecting with patients, so I’m thankful that i still have that opportunity.⁣
⁣
I think what gets to me and my amazing staff is the grind of screening patients and what-feels-like constant cleaning. And we all know that by working in healthcare that we are taking on risk of exposure for ourselves and, by extension, our families.⁣
⁣
We are all so grateful for our patients (we love you!), but it’s a hard pill to swallow to see people gathering in groups of 200,000+. And it’s hard to see our town packed with people who aren’t practicing any precautions. Because we know that those are the actions that are gonna extend our daily grind and burden the rest of the healthcare system. Sigh...⁣
⁣
Now I have a 4 day weekend. Goals? Catch up with work, which is normal on my days off. Small business owners know what I mean ?⁣
⁣
But my main goal is to take some action so that I can bounce back from this funk. It’s a chance to build some resiliency, right? And I’m always up for a challenge.⁣
⁣
?? ?’? ????????? ??? ?? ?? ???? ??? ?? ???? ?????⁣
⁣
I’m going to tap into the power of cuddling puppies, gardening, exercise, and making food. But I’d love to hear some new ideas from Insta-land!⁣
⁣
All right, I’m going to leave this post alone now and I’m looking forward to reading your comments. If you don’t want to comment with your funk-busting tips, please DM me!

Posted @withregram • @hebontheweb idk who needs to hear this but the pandemic isn’t over just because you’re over it. 
#pandemic #coronavirus #covid19

node.text:
To put things kinda in perspective about the #derecho that hit Iowa on Monday, August 10, Hurricane Sandy was a Category 3 hurricane with max winds up to 115mph and EVERYONE was hearing about it for weeks. The top windspeed reported in Iowa's storms was 130mph (Category 3 hurricane levels!) in Midway, IA. The Cedar Rapids surrounding area had up to 106mph (Cat. 2) winds. NOT. A. SINGLE. NEWS. SOURCE. IS. TALKING. ABOUT. US.

Many people have extensive #damage to their homes, vehicles, and other property. There are widespread power outages, with many people likely not going to be able to get power back until the end of the week at earliest! People are out of a home, jobs, food, gas for their vehicles, and running on very little money in an already struggling time due to the #pandemic. 

If you have friends or family in #Iowa, please keep them in mind bc so far we've gotten virtually ZERO help and no major news source is spreading the stories of what has happened to us. This isn't okay, Iowa isn't okay.

????UPDATE 8/13/2020????: It seems the news of what has happened to us is slowly being shared around the country, which is great! HOWEVER, despite being announced in a state of emergency, no FEMA, Red Cross, or National Guard deployment to help us has happened. Citizens have had to call Red Cross themselves because Governor Reynolds couldn't care less. This isn't just the cities impacted, it's the small towns, it's the #farmers. Everyone is devastated and the government has done NOTHING to help its people.

La enfermedad de Alzheimer (EA) es la principal causa de demencia entre los adultos mayores (salvo en los japoneses, donde predomina la demencia vascular). Es una enfermedad de compleja patogenia, a veces hereditaria, que se caracteriza desde el punto de vista anato?mico, por pe?rdida de neuronas y sinapsis y la presencia de placas seniles y de degeneracio?n neurofibrilar. Cli?nicamente se expresa como una demencia de comienzo insidioso y lentamente progresiva, que habitualmente se inicia con fallas de la memoria reciente y termina con un paciente postrado en cama, totalmente dependiente. ( introduccin de Archibaldo Donoso, La enfermedad de Alzheimer, Revista chilena de neuro-psiquiatra)
No recordar no significa que no existio?

node.text:
THE PANDEMIC SCHOOL TRANSPORTATION CONUNDRUM 

The logistics of School Transportation when there is no Pandemic is difficult but during a Pandemic is ABSOLUTELY A CONUNDRUM.

The big problem that I've noticed parents discussing most often is the lack of information that they have with regard to the School District's actual plans for transportation. Parents only see what is RECOMMENDED in the news media. They have not received any detailed information from their district on precisely what WILL AND WILL NOT OCCUR with regard to transportation in their district. This is the most comprehensive written information that I have been able to find on Transportation.  If your district is using this great and if they are not feel free to provide this to them as a recommendation.

The only concern that I have with regard to this is that illistration for seating arrangements without masks alludes to the thought that the wearing of a mask somehow allows social distancing grace. The CDC recommendations do not define hand washing, the where of a mask, and social distancing as interchangeable protective measures. You cannot excuse yourself from wearing a mask just because you decide to wash your hands frequently. You cannot excuse yourself from social distancing just because you've decided to wear a mask. That said, transportation needs to re-assess proposed seating arrangements.

Parents please stay informed and be vigilant. Your children's health and safety depends on it.

?: @educationweek
?: Getting Kids to School: Tackling the COVID-19 Transportation Problem
?: Stephanie Shafer

Students matter and teachers who only call home when a student is misbehaving is missing out on the chance to build a real connection with the family!

1. Get to know your students by name AND interest
2. Check in with the family regularly for the good and bad
3. Be consistent. Students need solid, trustworthy adults in their life!

Today’s crescent moon signals the closing of this moon cycle. In the next few days, leading up to the new moon on Tuesday, you may feel the desire to be more active, experience an increase of emotional sensitivity and crave connection with others. If you can, spend time outside or open a window wide to take in some fresh air through deep cleansing breaths. This is a great way to let go of anything no longer serving you while giving your lungs some love and gratitude. Nurture yourself with a simple hand massage, this will help release some tension and stress your hands may be feeling due to the Gemini Moon. 
Follow your inner voice calling out for you to connect and surround yourself with empowered women. You deserve to say yes to the support of a community of like-minded goddesses! Tag your bff and save yourself a spot on the upcoming "Women's Tools to Navigate Uncertain Times" webinar:  Click link in bio

To my fellow vets out there: I think we can all agree that practicing veterinary medicine in the middle of this pandemic has been tough! Check out @petproconnect and see how it makes our lives a little easier. It’s an all-in-one platform that makes virtual communication with clients MUCH more convenient. For example, you can easily schedule tele-health chats to help with curbside protocols. You can also message clients in real time, freeing up your clinic to do more throughout the day. It’s completely free as well, so check them out and request a demo for your clinic!

? Victoria's Secret declared bankruptcy.
? Zara is closing 1200 stores.
? Chanel, Hermes and Rolex have stopped production.
? Nike is getting ready for stage two of layoffs.
? AirBnb founder says that due to the pandemic, 12 years of effort were destroyed in 6 weeks.
? Starbucks announced the permanent closure of 400 stores.
And the list continues...

5?⃣ months since the pandemic started and it has created huge ? debts, many of our friends and family are out of work and unemployed with tens of thousands of businesses ? now out of service.?

If the company? you work for continues, no pay reduction or layoffs, then treat it well ?? and have respect for what the owner must be going through to keep it going.

2020 is about survival, leave the daily complaints/moans/groans ? and anything else minor behind, be thankful?? for what you have‼?

If you decided to start being your own boss ??‍? and work from home ? during these crazy times, stay CONSISTENT and focused ? on your goals... dream BIGGER!!

? We are in such a powerful time where entrepreneurship is back stronger than ever.

? Now is NOT the time to quit.

Now is the time to go ? ALL IN.
Play every hand ? .
Show up ??‍?? when no one else is.
Show others that mountains ? can be moved.

Not for others. For YOU??. So at the end of this season you can truly and honestly look at yourself in the mirror say “I gave it my all” ????

Image may contain: text that says 'In the state of Maryland, 72% of parents with children in special education believed that their child's skills declined during the COVID-19 pandemic due to distance learning. Maryland -The @Mustard Seed Mom'.

node.text:
The Arc Maryland has been hearing from parents that eLearning has been very challenging. With most school systems announcing plans to be virtual again in the fall, there has been a growing interest and need to address how the local school system and state recovery plans are impacting children who receive special education services and their families. In one of the polls conducted on Wednesday night, 72% of respondents said they believed their child's skills have declined during distance learning. Parents overwhelmingly remarked that the special education/continuity of their child's learning was a concern and the related services -that are necessary for children to access a Free and Appropriate Public Education (FAPE)- were diminished or not provided at all, resulting in loss of educational progress.

Source: The Arc Maryland

node.text:
The beginning of the weather change. Everything is shifting. Pay attention to the Schumann resonance. The mass Exodus of the State of California is on everyone's lips.. Phoenix has already had a record-setting summer, setting a new mark for most days 110 degrees or higher in a single year with 36, a number that's expected to climb over the next 7 days as temperatures soar to 115 degrees.

And Death Valley, considered the hottest place on Earth, is forecast to reach 126 degrees on Sunday and 127 degrees on Monday. If this happens, that will be the hottest temperature recorded so late in the year.

Noah Diffenbaugh, a professor of earth system science at Stanford University, said the impact of severe heat tends to fall disproportionately on marginalized groups, including people experiencing homelessness and families struggling with poverty.

People who do not have access to quality housing and air conditioning tend to be more vulnerable to heat, he said, and families with limited economic resources generally do not get as much urgent attention from emergency response systemsLast year, California's population growth slowed to 1900 levels after it experienced a mass exodus of residents. From mid-2018 to mid-2019, California experienced a 0.35 percent growth rate, while recording a 0.57 percent growth rate in 2018. ... Since 1991, California has undergone net domestic out-migration.Instead of a gold rush, it looks like California is experiencing a mass exodus. 2020 - what a crazy almost 8 months it has been ?
Are you minding your mental health during these times ? 
The pandemic has done some serious damage, and has caused so much pain. Emotional and financial struggles for families.

But not having a cuddle from a loved one or friends over for a cuppa on the sofa the small things we miss !! ? Let's try fill insgagram with some love and positive vibes and see the rest of 2020 out with a clearer and healthier mindset ? Lets connect and check in with people ? 
We have got this ?

node.text:
I am horrified by what is going on in the name of the so-called "greater good". In the words of John Pilger: "A pandemic has been declared, but not for the 24,600 who die every day from unnecessary starvation, and not for 3,000 children who die every day from preventable malaria, and not for the 10,000 people who die every day because they are denied publicly-funded healthcare, and not for the hundreds of Venezuelans and Iranians who die every day because America's blockade denies them life-saving medicines, and not for the hundreds of mostly children bombed or starved to death every day in Yemen, in a war supplied and kept going, profitably, by America and Britain. Before you panic, consider them".

Betraying ourselves, people pleasing and fawning are trauma responses. I used to be a people pleaser, or a "good girl', until the price of betraying myself was worse than the risk of losing or disappointing people. I still see this pattern/fear in myself from time to time.⁣
⁣
The thing most on my mind lately is how children are being affected by how the world's governments are responding to the pandemic. It breaks my heart to hear the "new normal" being normalised, because there is *nothing* normal about it.⁣
⁣
This is my truth and opinion: we are setting our children up for massive traumatisation if we don't stand up for choice, agency and freedom. I am traumatised by what is going on, what is it doing to children and what will it do to their futures? Many countries can no longer be called democracies and we are inching ever closer to totalitariansim.⁣
⁣
Back in March we believed that covid19 could be very serious and we took the necessary precautions. We have since found out that the recovery rate is 99.8%, thank goodness. I know people have died and it is always sad, but humans die every day. Covid case counts do not equal covid deaths counts.⁣
⁣
To quote some real world statistics fromworldometers.info, this year, there have been 522,592 deaths from water related diseases, 302,899 flu deaths, 4,717,045 children under 5 have died, 5,096,767 deaths from cancer, 3,102,296 deaths form smoking, 665,478 deaths from suicide. What is the real pandemic facing us? Are we ignoring the pink elephant in the room?⁣
⁣
We have evolved with bacteria and viruses for millions of years. Are we going to lockdown, quarantine healthy people, wear masks, and force vaccinations on people for existing viruses and new ones to come? Is it sustainable? Or should we concentrate on strengthening our immune systems and looking after our vulnerable properly, not just for public relations spin?⁣ ?

I look forward to the day that stamps can be slapped on my passport. Or being able to show my ticket and ID to the cranky man/woman with their light & suspicious stare. Enjoying the overpriced coffee, blueberry muffin and hearing languages I haven’t heard in person before. Witnessing families reuniting. Arriving to a new destination, full of life, excited, yet in desperate need of a shower after spending 3 minutes in an airport. All of it, without a fucking pandemic attached. 

Man good times. ? Bring it back. #airport #passport #pandemic #coffee #icedcoffee #traveling #global #airplane #abroad #bringitback #travel #muffin #overpriced #ineed #vacation

node.text:
The interesting fact is that failure is just a matter of understanding that we are not getting results in a way we have desired for.

There is no one in this world, who have not been failed at some point of their lives.

Whether, be it the big names like Ratan Tata, Sachin Tendulkar, Sonu Sood etc. or the small names like me, you and millions, trillions of peoples like us, all have gone / are going through the failures at one or another point of their journey of life.

But, important is to understand that some takes their failure as the learning lessons to identify that what is working? and what is not working?. So, after knowing, they start to improve and grow further. This is how they glows and we start calling them the big names or in other words we start to follow them / read their life journeys in order to motivate ourselves.

Now, the questions are - 

How do you deal with your failures?

What have you learnt from your failures?

What motivates you to continue your journey after failure?

Share your thoughts and enrich us with your valuable inputs.

node.text: Meanwhile, some cringey Tik Tokers and shit YouTubers who make millions are busy complaining when asked to wear a mask. Why is the world full of undeserving pieces of shit? She deserves more money as she is saving lives.
Easily the worlds biggest shithole country
Such real-life lessons we better learn- to call the nurse not a hero, but treat her as a human!
That is modern medicine for you.  Money always goes to the administrators first, and then the hard workers.

Don't call this nurse a hero. She doesn't want to hear it. ⁣⁠
⁣⁠
Michelle Gonzalez, 30, is a registered nurse in the Bronx. She contracted COVID-19 after reusing the same mask for a week.⁣⁠
⁣⁠
"We were losing our minds with the trauma of knowing that we tried to care for patients, and most people had a patient die every shift."⁣⁠
⁣⁠
The U.S. has the most coronavirus cases globally, with more than 5.2 million cases and 160,000 deaths. More than 900 health care workers may have died from COVID-19 since March.⁣⁠
⁣⁠
In April, New York Governor Andrew Cuomo cut the budget for Medicaid, which Gonzalez says insures about 60% of patients at her hospital.⁣⁠
⁣⁠
"Now we're cutting funding. It almost feels like you want us all to die here … I think health care is meant to be equal for every single person, regardless of income or education. Everything is so geared to profit, you've neglected the patients."⁣⁠
⁣⁠
The coronavirus pandemic has hit working-class people the hardest, especially people of color. It's a "clear-cut example of classism," says Gonzalez.⁣⁠
⁣⁠
"In the Bronx, unfortunately, we have a lot of poverty in my neighborhood ... We had high rates of diabetes, hypertension, cardiovascular disorders. All these things hurt this population's ability to fight COVID."⁣⁠
⁣⁠
Click the link in our bio to subscribe to subtext, our newsletter, to read more interviews like this.⁣⁠
⁣⁠
⁣⁠

node.text:
Lionsgate Portal ended yesterday.

I am grateful for the powerful lessons I have learned between the 26th of July and yesterday. An intense transition period where I received many insights, as well as many suprising and exciting news from friends and family. Old themes came up to be looked in the eye and burried back in.

And now I feel the mud that has been moved up and can go settle back in and find a new place.

Ever since the begining of June I sense an intense end to 2020 with a cathartic month of September so I am chillin as much as I can until then.

Embracing laziness is also part of the Lion's month. Imagine the royal animal just laying in the sun waiting for the lioness to bring him food. I can really relate to that feeling today. 

We judge ourselves so often for not hustling enough. We take pride in being busy-busy. We ask questions like: "so what is up with you? What's new?"and feel almost deceived when nothing new has happened. We think we or other are boring. 

We forget that life is still happening in the nothingness and that actually. These boring moments of your life are the most fruitful for they bary the seeds of creativity and renewal.

On August 18tht we have a New Moon in Leo. Lets take advantage of this day to prepare for what is coming, release the old and welcome the new. 

Welcome the darkness, the emptyness, the boredom, the cluenesness, lack of ideas and motivation!

How about you? What energies are you feeling at the moment? How do you feel about the month of September 2020?

I wish you all a very happy and lazy month of August!

Namaste

node.text:
? HOW YA DOUGH’N?

Yet another local business born during COVID-19! From scratch - sour dough pizzas!! 

What started out as a way to stay connected to friends in the neighborhood - passing pizzas over the fence while saying a quick hi - has become so much more.

Garett Goodman has been working from home (Boca Raton) since the Pandemic, and in his spare time, started making pizzas from scratch for some of the neighborhood kids. Garrett always loved making pizzas, but now...

Before you could say, HOW YA DOUGH’N, Garett has found himself with a full fledged business! Kinda! 

Garett makes the pizzas at home (slide to see the set-up), and is currently posting menus on Mondays and Wednesdays, through the link in the 
@howyadoughn bio on Insta, for pick up Wednesdays and Fridays.

Slide ?? to see the deliciousness. Brussel Sprouts and Proper Bacon, the Arrabbiata Special, and the Margarita pizzas. Sooo yummy. 

If you live in South Florida and want to place an order, DO IT! Pick up times are between 3-7p.m. @howyadoughn accepts payment through @venmo.

Let’s remember to #supportlocal and each other, because #wereallinthistogether, and it’s the neighborly thing to do! Plus.... PIZZA! 

Side Note: Starting a petition for Garett to open a restaurant when the time is right! Wanna sign up??

#pizza #pizzalover #selfmade

node.text:
WHAT REALLY IS TELEMEDECINE/TELEHEALTHCARE?

Used interchangeably, the idea of telemedicine/telehealth care might have seemed like science fiction a decade ago, but that is far from the case today.

Things like smartphones and the Internet have now shown that it is very much possible to get quality healthcare service, remotely.

While this is still being met with some hesitation, people are motivated by its extreme convenience and accessibility.

And, the rapid advancement of technology each day has widely contributed to investments in its adoption, especially with the global COVID-19 pandemic.

Researchers have divided telehealth encounters into e-consult, follow-up visits, medication management, remote patient monitoring, management of chronic diseases, and a host of other clinical services.

The Internet, mobile applications, and technologies now serve as a passageway to resources that are currently unavailable, especially in rural areas.

In light of the pandemic, messages in the health world have evolved to optimize ways for patient care but limit the spread of the virus. 

It is predicted that, in the nearest future, telemedicine will become more of an integral part of the healthcare system and our lives in general.

Reposted from @rosetangy: Stoked to play a live #gig , finally, after months (I don't even remember) of #clusterfuck situations! We'll be playing at H0L0's outdoor bar (address in poster) around the corner from H0L0's entrance, Ridgewood, Queens. our set is at 8pm, just before the film screenings. The whole event will also be livestreamed (see details in the poster). 

This gig is particularly historical (for us band members @danielcarternyc @_evan_strauss_ @the1truegoiter & me ). Our band "On The Way!" @ontheway718 debutted at @h0l0.nyc in May, 2018. Sver since then, many bridges under the water, and vice versa. Now back at H0L0, the legendary music venue in Queens, our reunion gig is, sadly, a send off gig, for Evan, who's moving out of NYC. May our sonic web expand even bigger as bandmates move out and around. This ain't the end, this is the beginning of beginning. Good luck with everything out in the West, Evan! 

Also looking forward to seeing Ben Tripp's new movie! Thank you Ben @tripp.benjamin for inviting us to play and for organizing such a unique and fun event. Also looking forward to seeing @gene_baker_llc @theoriginalpaintedfaces play!
